Introduction to Lie group methods

with a focus on matrix groups.

Author: Alexander Johan Arntzen

Date: 23.11.2021

What is a Lie group?

Definition

A Lie group GG is a smooth manifold that is also a group, such that multiplication

:GGG(1)(1):GGG

and inversion

i:GG(2)(2)i:GG are smooth.

Matrix Lie grops

We note that the matrix group of nnnn invertible matrices GLn(R)GLn(R) is a Lie group with normal matrix multiplication and matrix inverse.

To avoid dealing to many details we restrict ourselves to the matrix gruops and its subgroup.

Matrix lie group example SO(n)SO(n)

An interesting example of a Lie group is the Special Orthogonal Group SO(n)SO(n). This is the group of orthonormal matrices {Q:QTQ=I}{Q:QTQ=I}

Now consider a curve QQ with Q(t)=IQ(t)=I. Then

ddtQQT=Q+QT=0(3)(3)ddtQQT=Q+QT=0

So at e=Ie=I the all derivatives of curves will be skew symmetric. We call the space of derivatives at ee the Lie algebra.

The exponential map

Consider an initial value problem on a matrix Lie group

Y=AYY(0)=Y0Y=AYY(0)=Y0

Then we know that Y(t)=exp(tA)Y0Y(t)=exp(tA)Y0 solves this equation. This is called the exponential map and generalises beyond matrix groups.

Lie group action

A Lie group can act on a smooth manifold MM with action :GMM:GMM satisfying:

1) ex=xex=x

2) g(hx)=ghxg(hx)=ghx

A Lie group action is transitive if mM gGmM gG such that m=gxm=gx

Integration on manifolds

Problem

We consider a vector field XX on the smooth manifold MM resulting in the initial value problem

y=X(y)y(0)=y0y=X(y)y(0)=y0

for any y0My0M.

If we try to use normal Runge-Kutta schemes we might end up outside the manifold.

Example of why RK might fail

We consider an initial value problem on SO(n)SO(n), with vector field X(Y)=A(Y)YX(Y)=A(Y)Y, where A(Y) is a skew symmetric matrix and Y(0)=Y0Y(0)=Y0.

If we use forward euler we get:

Y1=Y0+hA(Y0)Y0.(4)(4)Y1=Y0+hA(Y0)Y0.

We check that we are still inn SO(n)SO(n)

YT1Y1=(Y0+hA(Y0)Y0)T(Y0+hA(Y0)Y0)=Ih2YT0A(Y0)2Y0I(5)(5)Y1TY1=(Y0+hA(Y0)Y0)T(Y0+hA(Y0)Y0)=Ih2Y0TA(Y0)2Y0I

Solution: Take steps using the exponential map

Using the exponential map we easily get the Lie Euler method

Y1=expA(hY0)Y0(6)(6)Y1=expA(hY0)Y0

Notice:

  • The first step integrates the vector field X(Y)=A(Y0)YX(Y)=A(Y0)Y
  • The coincides with forward Euler up to order 2
  • The method has order 1

Methods based on freezing the vector field

Assume we have set of vector fields {E1,...,Ed}{E1,...,Ed} such that for any vector field XX and yy in MM :

X(y)=di=1fi(y)Ei(y).(7)(7)X(y)=i=1dfi(y)Ei(y).

Then the frozen vector field at pp is then defined as

Xp(y)=di=1fi(p)Ei(y).(8)(8)Xp(y)=i=1dfi(p)Ei(y).

The idea is then to take steps using this frozen vector field.

Example

Consider the vector field X(Y)=A(Y)Y, A(Y)gX(Y)=A(Y)Y, A(Y)g. Here the frozen vector field at point pp is the vector field A(p)YA(p)Y.

This is integrated exactly by the exponential map.

Crouch and Grossman methods

Crouch and Grossman methods calculates the frozen vector fields and takes steps using one vector field.

Fo Butcher Tableau :

01241241724161246123230124124172416124612323

we get:

K1=Y0K2=exp(h/24A(K1))Y0K3=exp(6hA(K2))exp(161/24hA(K1))Y0Y1=exp(2/3hA(K3))exp(2/3hA(K2))exp(hA(K1))Y0,K1=Y0K2=exp(h/24A(K1))Y0K3=exp(6hA(K2))exp(161/24hA(K1))Y0Y1=exp(2/3hA(K3))exp(2/3hA(K2))exp(hA(K1))Y0,

Commutator-free methods

Commutator free methods can use linear combinations of all frozen vector fields in the exponential.

For Butcher Tableau :

0131323023130011203401313230231300112034

we get:

K1=Y0K2=exp(h/3A(K1))Y0K3=exp(2/3hA(K1))Y0Y1=exp(1/12hA(K1))+3/4hA(K2))K2,K1=Y0K2=exp(h/3A(K1))Y0K3=exp(2/3hA(K1))Y0Y1=exp(1/12hA(K1))+3/4hA(K2))K2,

RK-MK methods

Assume that MM is acted upon transitively by a Lie group G. Then any curve in MM can be written on the form y(t)=g(t)y0y(t)=g(t)y0.

Furthermore, in neighborhood of y(0)y(0)

y(t)=exp((t))y(0)(9)(9)y(t)=exp((t))y(0)

One then approximates (t)(t) ending up with the resulting methods:

Ki=dexp1iaijKjA(exp(hjaijKj)y0), i=1,...,sY1=exp(hsi=1biki)y0Ki=dexpiaijKj1A(exp(hjaijKj)y0), i=1,...,sY1=exp(hi=1sbiki)y0

These methods have the advantage that they preserve the order of the original RK method.

Euler free rigid body equations

We now test the methods on the Euler free rigid body equations

L=skew(I1L)L,(10)(10)L=skew(I1L)L,

where L=diag(Iy,Iy,Ix)L=diag(Iy,Iy,Ix) and

skew(v)=0v3v2v30v1v2v10(11)(11)skew(v)=[0v3v2v30v1v2v10]

Note: The equation has form X(Y)=A(t)YX(Y)=A(t)Y, and LTLLTL is constant.

Numerical results

In [4]:
t_0 = 0
t_f = 100
h = 1e-3

y_0 = np.array([1, 4, 2])
I_x = 1
I_y = 2
I_z = 3
I = np.diag([I_x, I_y, I_z])
I_inv = np.linalg.inv(I)


def F(y,):
    return skew(I_inv @ y)

def Ft(t,y):
    return skew(I_inv @ y) @ y

print("euler ")
y_eul, T = lie_euler(F, y_0=y_0, t_0=t_0, t_f=t_f, h=h, exp=so3_exp)
print("com_free")
y_com, T = com_free_3(F, y_0=y_0, t_0=t_0, t_f=t_f, h=h, exp=so3_exp)
print("CG")
y_cro, T = crouch_grossmann_3(F, y_0=y_0, t_0=t_0, t_f=t_f, h=h, exp=so3_exp)
print("RKMK")

y_rkmk, T = rkmk_3(F, y_0=y_0, t_0=t_0, t_f=t_f, h=h, exp=so3_exp)
print("RK45")
rk_sol= si.solve_ivp(Ft,(t_0,t_f), y_0,max_step=h, method="RK23")
